<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="381" pageId="3" pageNumber="379" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,612,638]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[351,458,612,638]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Holotype</typeStatus>
, male (
<figureCitation box="[536,636,612,638]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[179,1397,185,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[179,1409,179,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Dilatapolochrus vikhrevi Tshernyshev gen. et sp.n., holotype, male, external appearance, dorsal view (1); external appearance, lateral view (2); left antenna (3); left anterior tarsus (4); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, dorsal view (5); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, lateral view (6); left leg, dorsal view (7); left leg, ventral view (8); pygidium (9); ultimate abdominal ventrite (10); aedeagus, dorsal view (11); tegmen (12); distribution map (13). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736851" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736851/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Figs 1, 2</figureCitation>
). Body elongate, oval, slightly expanded posteriorly, elytra not covering three ultimate segments of the abdomen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Body black-brown with a weak green-blue metallic luster, second antennomere and apical part of the first antennomere, clypeus and commissure membranes of ventrites yellow. Surface evenly covered with pale brown pubescence, long and erect, head also with semi-erect pale hairs. Vesicles yellow, and thoracic mesepimera blackbrown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Head narrower than pronotum, flat, interocular area almost completely flat, eyes simple, not large, slightly protruding, round-oval, frons flat; genae short and straight; clypeus slightly elongate, transverse, straight; labrum narrow, transverse; palpi simple with apical segment slightly elongate, narrow, sub-oval and truncate at apex; surface of head evenly and finely punctured with distinct microsculpture, densely covered with short pale brown fine adpressed pubescence.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">
Antennae with flattened and widened 6th to 11th antennomeres (
<figureCitation box="[921,988,1008,1034]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[179,1397,185,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[179,1409,179,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Dilatapolochrus vikhrevi Tshernyshev gen. et sp.n., holotype, male, external appearance, dorsal view (1); external appearance, lateral view (2); left antenna (3); left anterior tarsus (4); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, dorsal view (5); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, lateral view (6); left leg, dorsal view (7); left leg, ventral view (8); pygidium (9); ultimate abdominal ventrite (10); aedeagus, dorsal view (11); tegmen (12); distribution map (13). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736851" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736851/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), 
<quantity box="[1010,1096,1008,1035]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="379" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
long, expanding over the base of elytra; 1st antennomere slightly enlarged, subrectangular with rounded angles, 2nd antennomere small, round, almost completely invisible, strongly hidden by the 1st antennomere, 3rd antennomere elongate, as long as the 1st antennomere and 1.5 times narrower, 3rd, 4th and 5th antennomeres short, subtriangular, 6th to 10th with expanded outer edges, 6th and 10th triangular, 7th to 9th antennomeres rectangular and 11th (apical one) elongate and oval, widened to apex; surface sparsely covered with fine short, brown adpressed pubescence.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Pronotum weakly narrowed at base, almost completely equilateral and sub-oval with evenly rounded angles, slightly depressed at the base and at the posterior angles, with posterior margin slightly elevate and swollen; anterior and posterior margins straight; lateral sides evenly rounded and flattened, distinctly marginate; very sparsely and finely punctured lacking microsculpture, shining, evenly covered with fine long erect pale brown hairs.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Scutellum rectangular, small and narrow, transverse, almost completely covered by pronotum, sparsely punctured and covered with brown short pubescence.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Elytra sub-oval, not covering three apical segments of the abdomen, slightly expanded just behind the base, at base not wider than pronotum, humeri small, distinct and protruding; apices evenly rounded, simple; disc distinctly and finely marginate on external sides and widely along suture, edge of suture is restricted near apices of elytra; surface shining, densely and coarsely punctured, with distinct microsculpture, evenly covered with pale-brown long erect pubescence.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" box="[199,423,1620,1646]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Hind wings normal.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,468,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">
Legs thin, slightly elongate; posterior femora almost completely reaching elytral apices; anterior tibiae dilated and strongly excavated in apical half so the basal lobe appears to have a flattened oval plate above (
<figureCitation box="[1316,1422,1692,1719]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[179,1397,185,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[179,1409,179,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Dilatapolochrus vikhrevi Tshernyshev gen. et sp.n., holotype, male, external appearance, dorsal view (1); external appearance, lateral view (2); left antenna (3); left anterior tarsus (4); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, dorsal view (5); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, lateral view (6); left leg, dorsal view (7); left leg, ventral view (8); pygidium (9); ultimate abdominal ventrite (10); aedeagus, dorsal view (11); tegmen (12); distribution map (13). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736851" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736851/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
), intermediate tibiae stout, with three deep round-oval impressions near apices at ventral side (
<figureCitation box="[1210,1313,1728,1755]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[179,1397,185,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[179,1409,179,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Dilatapolochrus vikhrevi Tshernyshev gen. et sp.n., holotype, male, external appearance, dorsal view (1); external appearance, lateral view (2); left antenna (3); left anterior tarsus (4); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, dorsal view (5); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, lateral view (6); left leg, dorsal view (7); left leg, ventral view (8); pygidium (9); ultimate abdominal ventrite (10); aedeagus, dorsal view (11); tegmen (12); distribution map (13). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736851" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736851/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Figs 7, 8</figureCitation>
), posterior tibiae simple, straight; anterior femora slightly widened and evenly impressed in middle, sides of the impression covered with a row of short erect hairs (
<figureCitation box="[592,658,1800,1827]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[179,1397,185,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[179,1409,179,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Dilatapolochrus vikhrevi Tshernyshev gen. et sp.n., holotype, male, external appearance, dorsal view (1); external appearance, lateral view (2); left antenna (3); left anterior tarsus (4); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, dorsal view (5); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, lateral view (6); left leg, dorsal view (7); left leg, ventral view (8); pygidium (9); ultimate abdominal ventrite (10); aedeagus, dorsal view (11); tegmen (12); distribution map (13). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736851" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736851/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), all other femora slightly widened and simple, lacking emarginations or indentations; trochanters simple, lacking teeth, elongate; all tarsi 5-segmented, intermediate tarsomeres slightly compressed, apical one flattened, not long, first tarsomere elongate, sub-triangular and the longest of all legs, 2nd segment in anterior tarsi triangular, with small transversal comb above (
<figureCitation box="[966,1035,1908,1934]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[179,1397,185,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[179,1409,179,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Dilatapolochrus vikhrevi Tshernyshev gen. et sp.n., holotype, male, external appearance, dorsal view (1); external appearance, lateral view (2); left antenna (3); left anterior tarsus (4); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, dorsal view (5); tibia and tarsus of left anterior leg, lateral view (6); left leg, dorsal view (7); left leg, ventral view (8); pygidium (9); ultimate abdominal ventrite (10); aedeagus, dorsal view (11); tegmen (12); distribution map (13). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736851" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736851/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="379">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), in intermediate and posterior legs it is 1.3 times shorter than the 1st tarsomere, 1.3 times as long as the 3rd and twice as long as the 4th; the 3rd and 4th tarsomeres in anterior legs small, equal in length and each twice as short as the 2nd tarsomere; claw-segment elongate and narrow in all legs; claws short, thin, narrow and sharp, with round transparent membrane at base.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4736851" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4736851" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4736851/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="380" startId="4.[151,264,1900,1924]" targetBox="[179,1397,185,1875]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1900,2033]" pageId="4" pageNumber="380">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,329,1900,1924]" pageId="4" pageNumber="380">FIGURES 1–13.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Tshernyshev" authorityName="Tshernyshev" authorityYear="2021" box="[338,729,1901,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Dilatapolochrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="380" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vikhrevi" status="gen. et sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[338,594,1901,1925]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="380">Dilatapolochrus vikhrevi</emphasis>
Tshernyshev
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[738,870,1901,1925]" pageId="4" pageNumber="380">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[738,870,1901,1925]" pageId="4" pageNumber="380" rank="species">gen. et sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
